# UI Implementation Rules for Thailand Real Estate Project

## Global CSS Architecture

### Primary Rule: Always Use Global CSS
- **NEVER** create inline styles or component-specific CSS files
- **ALWAYS** use the global CSS file: `resources/css/app.css`
- **ALWAYS** extend the existing CSS custom properties (CSS variables) defined in the `@theme` layer
- Use Tailwind utility classes for layout and spacing, but extend global CSS variables for theming

### CSS Variable Usage
- Use existing CSS custom properties from `resources/css/app.css`:
  - Color system: `--color-primary`, `--color-secondary`, `--color-surface`, etc.
  - Text colors: `--color-on-surface`, `--color-on-background`
  - Border colors: `--color-outline`, `--color-divider`
  - Status colors: `--color-success`, `--color-danger`, `--color-warning`
- When adding new colors or design tokens, add them to the `@theme` layer in `app.css`
- Maintain consistency by reusing existing variables rather than creating new ones

### Design System Principles

#### Modern Real Estate Design for Thailand
- **Color Palette**: Use warm, inviting colors that reflect Thai architecture and culture
  - Primary colors should convey trust and professionalism (blues, teals)
  - Accent colors should evoke luxury and premium properties (golds, deep purples)
  - Natural tones for property listings (greens, earth tones)
- **Typography**: 
  - Use the defined font families: `--font-sans` (Instrument Sans) and `--font-barlow-condensed`
  - Maintain readability for property descriptions and Thai language support
- **Spacing**: Use consistent spacing scale (Tailwind's default scale)
- **Border Radius**: Use `--radius-radius` variable for consistent rounded corners

#### Real Estate Specific Components
- Property cards should use consistent styling from global CSS
- Property status badges should use: `--color-for-sale` and `--color-for-rent`
- Image galleries should maintain aspect ratios and use consistent borders
- Forms should use the global field styling defined in `[data-flux-field]`

### Code Organization

#### Adding New Styles
1. **First**: Check if existing CSS variables or Tailwind utilities can be used
2. **Second**: If new design tokens are needed, add them to the `@theme` layer in `app.css`
3. **Third**: If component-specific styles are absolutely necessary, add them to the `@layer base` or create a new `@layer components` in `app.css`
4. **Never**: Create separate CSS files for individual components or views

#### Dark Mode Support
- Always ensure new styles work with both light and dark modes
- Use CSS variables that automatically adapt (they're already defined in `.dark` class)
- Test color contrast for accessibility in both modes

### Best Practices

#### Maintainability
- Keep all styles centralized in `resources/css/app.css`
- Document new CSS variables with comments explaining their purpose
- Group related styles together (colors, typography, spacing, etc.)
- Use semantic naming for CSS variables (e.g., `--color-primary` not `--color-blue-500`)

#### Performance
- Avoid CSS-in-JS or runtime style generation
- Use CSS variables for dynamic theming instead of inline styles
- Leverage Tailwind's purging to remove unused styles

#### Thailand Real Estate Context
- Ensure designs are culturally appropriate for Thai market
- Support both Thai and English text display
- Consider mobile-first approach (high mobile usage in Thailand)
- Use imagery and icons that resonate with Thai real estate market
- Ensure color choices work well in tropical/light environments

### Examples

#### ✅ Good: Using Global CSS
```blade
<div class="bg-surface text-on-surface rounded-radius p-4">
    <h2 class="text-primary font-barlow-condensed">Property Details</h2>
</div>
```

#### ❌ Bad: Inline Styles
```blade
<div style="background-color: #fff; color: #1b1b18; border-radius: 8px; padding: 1rem;">
    <h2 style="color: #1e40af; font-family: 'Barlow Condensed';">Property Details</h2>
</div>
```

#### ✅ Good: Extending Global CSS
```css
/* In app.css @theme layer */
--color-property-featured: #f59e0b;
--color-property-premium: #8b5cf6;
```

#### ❌ Bad: Component-Specific CSS File
```css
/* Don't create: resources/css/components/property-card.css */
.property-card { ... }
```

### Migration Notes
- When refactoring existing components, move any inline styles or component CSS to `app.css`
- Update components to use CSS variables and Tailwind utilities
- Maintain backward compatibility during migration
